review_blob: A bit on the sweet side for me, I like my saisons a bit drier. The nose is great, tropical fruits and pepper, enjoyable brew, but when a good Fantme is your standard, its hard to be fair to other saisons. But a Canadian saison, which is a plus for me.
beer_name: Muskoka Moonlight Kettle Series #1: Summer Saison

review_blob: I love New Zealand hops even though I havent tried all of them, this was my first brew with Rakau hops, started nicely enough, nice bouquet and very pleasant on the tastebuds for the first few sips. As it warms up a bit, everything shifts and not for the best, Im afraid. Would like to taste the equivalent with Nelson Sauvin hops. Oh, wait, I already did (Mikkellers single hops series).
I want this to be the last beer to pass my lips before I breathe my last breath. Stunning, does exactly what the brewer was envisioning when he planned for this beer. Heavenly.

Pleasant surprise from local brewery. Beer pours cloudy gold, foam is thin, carbonation slows down after a couple of drinks, not much to say on the nose, but I get piney hops, caramel, cereals and much later after the fact, some stony fruits. Good session beer.
Good bittering hops, earthy, toast hits you up front, high carbonation, some subtle dark fruits, overall a good effort.

For some reason, it reminds me of a watered down version of Icelands Lava stout. Peaty, smoky, body is lacking somewhat, but then again, I shouldnt compare apples and oranges, this is not a smoked imperial stout, its a smoked Scotch ale. Not quite veering towards rauchbier, but kind of in between.

A new (?) red ale from BDH, dark reddish brown, hoppy, almost Scottish ale-like, hoppy, berry aftertaste. Alcohol comes through after about half a minute. Absolutely no deScription on the label, this could be a beer brewed for a depanneur, although it has bite. This is not an Abbey Dubbel, contrary to the tag listed.
beer_name: Les Brasseurs du Hameau La Rouspteuse

beer_brewer_name: Brasseurs du Saguenay - La Tour  Bires
review_blob: Pale amber, almost no head, low carbonation, faint caramel on the nose, caramel and very faint orange, thin body. I really wanted to like this, but Im underwhelmed.

beer_brewer_name: Brasseurs du Saguenay - La Tour  Bires
review_blob: Burnt orange color, good carbonation when pouring, unfortunately doesnt last. Almost no head, past due date? Rather dull in the mouth, alcohol comes out. Expected pucker inducing tartness not present. A bit watery. I would like to taste a fresh one, it might influence my rating, maybe not by much, though.

Tasted in a beer-tasting event, from a bottle, one of about 25 porters and stouts tasted that night. This one goes against the grain, vanilla, caramel, wheat, nice change from the standards. I can see why it would be off-putting, but it all makes sense after the third drink. Ill have to try it on its own to see if I still get the same rush.
